<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
    #154 reversed the #58 decision to keep this file empty. On macOS 26.4.1
    "hardened runtime alone" was enough to trigger TCC; macOS 26.5 tightened
    the prompting policy — tccd now refuses to show ANY Calendar/Reminders
    prompt for a hardened-runtime binary that lacks the matching
    personal-information entitlement:

        Prompting policy for hardened runtime; service: kTCCServiceCalendar
        requires entitlement com.apple.security.personal-information.calendars
        but it is missing
        Policy disallows prompt ... access denied

    Without these keys, a TCC row pinned to an old build's csreq (e.g. the
    pre-v1.7.1 ad-hoc era) can never heal: the re-prompt is policy-blocked and
    the denial is silent and permanent while every status API reports green.

    Both keys are unrestricted entitlements — valid for Developer ID
    distribution outside the App Store, no provisioning profile needed, and
    no extra notarization requirements.

    Do NOT remove these keys. EntitlementsPlistTests pins them in CI, and
    scripts/sign-and-notarize.sh re-verifies them on the signed binary.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.personal-information.calendars</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.personal-information.reminders</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
